DEPUTY National Police Commissioner Lieutenant- General Sindile Mfazi has died due to Covid-19 related complications. Mfazi (59) was responsible for crime detection. The National Police Commissioner, General Khehla Sitole, has described Mfazi as an exemplary leader who was dedicated to the cause of serving and protecting the people of South Africa. He said: “The SAPS has lost one of its reliable, dedicated and greatly respected leaders in the organisation. Lieutenant-General Mfazi led by example and served this country with distinction until his death. On behalf of the SAPS family, we extend our deepest condolences to his family, friends and colleagues,” said Sitole. ALSO READ: ZUMA SNAPPED INSIDE PRISON! Mfazi served as a member of the South African Police Service for 39 years and held a number of executive positions, including deputy police commissioner responsible for corporate services in the Western Cape from 2003 to 2008. He was later transferred to the Eastern Cape where he held the position of provincial head for crime intelligence. In 2018, Mfazi was appointed as deputy national commissioner responsible for management advisory services, and moved to Tshwane. In March last year, Mfazi moved to the position of deputy national commissioner responsible for crime detection.